[normal]Q35 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs Glindon:[bold] I note that the second criterion of the O
[normal]mbu
[normal]dsman A
[normal]ssociation is fairness, so how do you respond to the concern that the LGO might be more willing to risk judicial review with small 
[normal]organisations rather than large
[normal] ones with large budget
[normal]s—
[normal]for example
[normal],
[normal] local authorities?
[normal]Dr Martin[bold]: 
[normal]I might ask Mick to comment in a moment because he looks after our legal team
[normal].  
[normal]Clearly, if there is any public concern about fairness that is 
[normal]also 
[normal]a concern to us, but judicial reviews form a very small part of our work
[normal].  
[normal]I think there were 19 last year, which is about 1.1% of our cases
[normal].  
[normal]The important point is that we run a process whereby all parties, whether it is an individual complainant or a lo
[normal]cal authority, can be clear 
[normal]about
[normal] the evidence we are presenting and
[normal] can challenge
[normal] it.  
[normal]We have a process which allows for that.
[normal]Michael King[bold]: 
[normal]I think
[normal] this arose from a submission from a member of the public.  There
[normal] was 
[normal]a concern
[normal] that perhaps the potential cost of judicial review might lead u
[normal]s to pull our punches.  
[normal]I can give you an absolute assurance that that is 
[normal]not the case.  To stick with judicial review,
[normal] to challenge one of our decisions i
[normal]s very much the final step 
[normal]anybody would take
[normal].  
[normal]We recognise that that is not a realistic proposition, not least because the courts have made clear that the scope for challenging an ombudsman’s decision is very small
[normal].  
[normal]Our focus is on making sure that people have the
[normal] opportunity to engage with, 
[normal]are consulted on and have the opportunity to challenge our decision al
[normal]l the way through the process.  
[normal]During an investigation
[normal],
[normal] we will share any key documents with both parties to make sure they have sight of the evid
[normal]ence on which we are relying.  B
[normal]efore we make a decision, both parties will be consulted on what we call a provisional view
[normal].  
[normal]That sets out the decision we are minded to make, and both parties at the same time will have the opportunity to comment on that view
[normal]. We 
[normal]will take those comments on board 
[normal]before making a final decision.
[normal]Once we 
[normal]have made a final decision, if the complainant or 
[normal]council comes back to raise new issu
[normal]es, or to challenge a
[normal] fault in the decis
[normal]ion, we have an internal 
[normal]process where a different team manager who has not been involved in that case will re
[normal]view it and, if necessary, reopen that decision.  Therefore, l
[normal]ong before anybody gets anywhere near judicial review there are multiple steps by which they can be involved in shaping the decision an
[normal]d challenging it, if necessary.
[normal]Where somebody does issue proceedings for judicial review, there is a process called the pre-action protocol
[normal].  
[normal]That enables them to set out in advance the issues 
[normal]in our decision 
[normal]which they 
[normal]think are flawed.  
[normal]We take that very seriously
[normal].  
[normal]Every pre
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]action protocol letter goes across my desk
[normal].  
[normal]We have a case conference about it; we consider whether or not it raises serious doubts about the decision we have made
[normal].  
[normal]If it does, we will reopen that case
[normal].  
[normal]So far this year, we have had 13 pre-action protocol letters
[normal].  
[normal]We have considered every one of those in detail, and in two of those cases we have made the decision to reopen the 
[normal]case
[normal] and look at it again, and that is exactly what has happened
[normal].  
[normal]Judicial review is by no means the only way in which people can make sure they are involved in our decision making.
[normal]Q36 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs Glindon:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you for explaining
[normal] the 
[normal]process
[normal].  
[normal]One of 
[normal]t
[normal]he issu
