[normal]ombudsmen have.  
[normal]What impact do you think codification of the ombudsman’s discretion would have on the work?
[normal]Dr Martin[bold]: I
[normal]t is the case that the courts support the wide discretion of the ombudsman, and that is the frame
[normal]work within which we work.  I
[normal]t is important that we do not fetter our discretion
[normal], although
[normal] we do consider each case on its merits
[normal].  
[normal]We would always make sure we 
[normal]do th
[normal]at.  
[normal]You will be aware that, as part of our new business model, we now have a new assessment process and code which gives greater clarity about how we exercise our discretion.
[normal]Michael King[bold]: 
[normal]One of the things we have introduced as part of the new assessment process is a very clear code
[normal],
[normal] which sets out the way in which we will make decisions 
[normal]and 
[normal]about which investigations we will and will not undertake
[normal].  
[normal]I hasten to add that that is not a new barrier we have put in place for the public
[normal].  
[normal]These are decisions we have 
[normal]always made.
[normal]We are trying
[normal] to be much clearer and 
[normal]more 
[normal]consistent about how we make those decisions, and much more transparent with the public about t
[normal]he criteria on which we base those
[normal] decisions
[normal].  
[normal]That code has been sent to every MP in the country
